In C#, a thread is a thread, there is no difference between an &#39;IO thread&#39; and any other thread. I think your book may be misleading you if it uses those terms. The only thing that would make a thread an &#39;IO thread&#39; is if you decide that it can only be used to process IO operations, and you implement it that way.

However, there _is_ a difference between **blocking** operations, like `Thread.Sleep()` and `WaitHandle.WaitOne()`, and **non-blocking** operations, like `BeginGetResponse/EndGetResponse` and many of the APM methods.

 - A **blocking** operation will _put the thread to sleep_, so the thread is doing nothing, but it still exists and it still uses the same amount of memory.
 - A **non-blocking** operation _starts_ the operation, and then returns immediately. When the operation is complete, a wait handle is signalled _by the operating system_. The calling thread _does not_ get put to sleep.

The article [&#39;There Is No Thread&#39;][1] that was linked to on your other question gives a particularly good explanation of how this works. I think you understand this much already. So a naive implementation of `FromAsync` would look like this:

    public Task&lt;TResult&gt; FromAsync&lt;TResult&gt;(IAsyncResult asyncResult, Func&lt;IAsyncResult, TResult&gt; endMethod)
    {
        return Task.Run(() =&gt;
        {
            while (!asyncResult.IsCompleted)
                asyncResult.AsyncWaitHandle.WaitOne();

            return endMethod(asyncResult);
        });
    }

There&#39;s a problem with this, though - the call to `asyncResult.AsyncWaitHandle.WaitOne()` puts the thread to sleep, so this defeats the whole purpose of using a non-blocking method. So how do we wait for a `WaitHandle` without blocking the current thread? There is a method specifically for this purpose: [RegisterWaitForSingleObject()][2].

    public Task&lt;TResult&gt; FromAsync&lt;TResult&gt;(IAsyncResult asyncResult, Func&lt;IAsyncResult, TResult&gt; endMethod)
    {
        RegisteredWaitHandle handle;
        var tcs = new TaskCompletionSource&lt;object&gt;();

        void OnAsyncResultSignalled(object state, bool timedOut)
        {
            if (asyncResult.IsCompleted)
            {
                handle.Unregister(null);
                tcs.TrySetResult(endMethod(asyncResult));
            }
        }

        handle = ThreadPool.RegisterWaitForSingleObject(
            asyncResult.AsyncWaitHandle,
            OnAsyncResult,
            null,
            TimeSpan.MaxValue,
            false);

        return tcs.Task;
    }

I&#39;m no expert in this area, so I&#39;m sure it could implemented more efficiently, but this gives you the general idea.

I&#39;ve created a `TaskCompletionSource`, and registered a callback to be run when the AsyncResult&#39;s wait handle is signalled. This means that until the wait handle is signalled, this callback is not being executed, and no threads are being blocked.

Of course, you&#39;re probably then going to ask _&#39;how does RegisterWaitForSingleObject work&#39;_? As a very broad explanation, the thread pool keeps _one_ dedicated thread to wait for _all_ registered events. So _yes_, a thread is being blocked, but no matter how many events you register this way, only _one_ thread is being blocked. For more details on this, see [the following answer][3].


[1]: https://blog.stephencleary.com/2013/11/there-is-no-thread.html
[2]: https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/api/system.threading.threadpool.registerwaitforsingleobject?view=netframework-4.8
[3]: https://stackoverflow.com/a/37500329/2363967

